2500|$|In 1934, the Swiss Federal Assembly {{passed the}} Federal Act on Banks and Savings Banks (colloquially {{known as the}} Banking Law of 1934), which mainly {{concerned}} administrative matters such as <b>bank</b> <b>supervision.</b> A still widely accepted canard is that the secrecy provisions of the 1934 bill were motivated by attempts by Nazi Germany to investigate the assets of Jews and [...] "enemies of the state" [...] held in Switzerland. This is not, however, the case. Firstly, Swiss banking secrecy was not introduced in 1934, but rather reinforced; secondly, Swiss ruling circles performed the 1934 reinforcement without humanitarian motives in mind.|$|E
